\begin_layout Standard
Define the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,v\rangle_{c}=\int_{\Omega}c\bar{u}v=\int_{\Omega}\overline{cu}v=\langle cu,v\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,v\rangle=\int_{\Omega}\bar{u}v$
\end_inset

 .
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,\hat{A}v\rangle_{c}=\langle cu,(cv)''\rangle=\langle(cu)'',cv\rangle=\langle c\hat{A}u,v\rangle=\langle\hat{A}u,v\rangle_{c}$
\end_inset

, where we have used the self-adjointness of 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}/dx^{2}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle$
\end_inset

 from class.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\hat{A}^{*}$
\end_inset

 under the 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,v\rangle_{c}$
\end_inset

 inner product (which is a proper inner product for real 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}g=\delta(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

, and we determine this by evaluating both sides with an arbitrary test
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, using the distributional derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\nabla^{2}g)\{\psi\}=g\{-\nabla^{2}\psi\}$
\end_inset

 as in class.
 In cylindrical coordinates: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g\{-\nabla^{2}\psi\} & =-\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\int_{\epsilon}^{\infty}r\, dr\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\phi\, c\ln r\left[\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial r}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}\psi}{\partial\phi^{2}}\right]\\
 & =-c\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\phi\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\int_{\epsilon}^{\infty}dr\,\ln r\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial r}\right)-\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\int_{\epsilon}^{\infty}\frac{c\ln r}{r}\, dr\cancel{\left.\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial\phi}\right|_{0}^{2\pi}}\\
 & =-c\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\phi\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\left[\cancel{\left.r\ln r\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial r}\right|_{\epsilon}^{\infty}}-\int_{\epsilon}^{\infty}dr\,\cancel{\frac{\partial(\ln r)}{\partial r}}\left(\cancel{r}\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial r}\right)\right]\\
 & =c\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\phi\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\left.\psi\right|_{r=\epsilon}^{r=\infty}=-2\pi c\psi(\vec{0}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To get 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta{\psi}=\psi(\vec{0})$
\end_inset

, therefore, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{c=-1/2\pi}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}_{\sigma}=\hat{D}-\sigma I$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 identity matrix.
 Then it follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}^{*}=-\hat{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma I)^{*}=\sigma I$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is a real scalar and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is obviously self-adjoint) under the usual inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{w},\vec{w}'\rangle=\int_{\Omega}\vec{w}^{*}\vec{w}'$
\end_inset

 that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}_{\sigma}^{*}=-\hat{D}-\sigma I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}_{\sigma}+\hat{D}_{\sigma}^{*}=-2\sigma I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

