\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 4:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u/\partial t=\partial v/\partial x-\sigma u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial v/\partial t=\partial u/\partial x-\sigma v$
\end_inset

, so the only new terms are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 terms.
 In the discretized 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u/\partial t$
\end_inset

 equation, the left-hand side is evaluated at point 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and time 
\begin_inset Formula $n+0.5,$
\end_inset

 so we have to get 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{m}^{n+0.5}=\frac{u_{m}^{n}+u_{m}^{n+1}}{2}+O(\Delta t^{2})$
\end_inset

 by averaging (similarly to how we handled the Crank-Nicolson discretization
 in class).
 Similarly for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial v/\partial t$
\end_inset

 equation.
 Hence, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{u_{m}^{n+1}-u_{m}^{n}}{\Delta t}=\frac{v_{m+0.5}^{n+0.5}-v_{m-0.5}^{n+0.5}}{\Delta x}-\sigma\frac{u_{m}^{n+1}+u_{m}^{n}}{2},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{v_{m+0.5}^{n+0.5}-v_{m+0.5}^{n-0.5}}{\Delta t}=\frac{u_{m+1}^{n}-u_{m}^{n}}{\Delta x}-\sigma\frac{v_{m+0.5}^{n+0.5}+v_{m+0.5}^{n-0.5}}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{m}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{m+0.5}^{n+0.5}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

leap-frog
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{m}^{n+1}=\left(1+\frac{\sigma\Delta t}{2}\right)^{-1}\left[\left(1-\frac{\sigma\Delta t}{2}\right)u_{m}^{n}+\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(v_{m+0.5}^{n+0.5}-v_{m-0.5}^{n+0.5}\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{m+0.5}^{n+0.5}=\left(1+\frac{\sigma\Delta t}{2}\right)^{-1}\left[\left(1-\frac{\sigma\Delta t}{2}\right)v_{m+0.5}^{n-0.5}+\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(u_{m+1}^{n}-u_{m}^{n}\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>0,$
\end_inset

 so we are never dividing by zero in 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\sigma\Delta t/2$
\end_inset

, regardless of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, which is comforting.
\end_layout

